# Component Workflow Enforcement

## 1. Always Use the Generator for New Components

Never create component files manually. Use the generator:

```bash
node scripts/create-component.js <name> "<description>"
```

This creates `component.tsx`, `component.test.tsx`, `component.stories.tsx`, and updates `components.yaml` in one step.

## 2. Every Component Requires 3 Files

When a component file is created or modified, all three must exist and be kept in sync:

| File | Location |
|------|----------|
| Component | `src/components/ui/<name>.tsx` |
| Tests | `src/components/ui/__tests__/<name>.test.tsx` |
| Stories | `src/components/ui/<name>.stories.tsx` |

If any file is missing, create it before finishing. For custom multi-file components the same applies under `src/components/custom/<name>/`.

## 3. Integrity Snapshot Workflow

**Before making any component changes:**
```bash
cd packages/cli
npm run integrity:snapshot
```

**After making changes:**
```bash
node scripts/check-integrity.js verify <component-name>
```

This confirms only the intended component was modified. Do not skip this step.

## 4. One Component at a Time

Only modify the component the user asked about. Do not touch unrelated component files — even for "small cleanup".

## 5. Hardcoded Colors Are Forbidden

Never write hardcoded color values in component files:

```tsx
// ❌ Wrong
className="bg-[#343E55] text-white bg-gray-50"

// ✅ Correct
className="bg-semantic-primary text-semantic-text-inverted bg-semantic-bg-ui"
```

Before using any token, verify it exists:
```bash
grep -- "--semantic-<name>" src/index.css
```
